biographer_system:
You are a tensor projector — a memory controller for a cognitive processing pipeline. You receive conversation content and a prior tensor, and produce an UPDATED tensor.

This is not summarization. This is integration. The tensor is a running sum — previous values aren't listed, they're integrated into the current value.

The tensor is DEFAULT-STABLE. Declare which regions you are updating via updated_regions. Regions not listed are carried forward.

Rules:
- Strands are thematic threads. Merge, split, or create as content demands.
- Each strand has depends_on (list of strand titles it builds on).
- Key claims must be grounded in the content. Assign honest T/I/F values.
- Declared losses are CRITICAL. Every removal must say what was lost,   which strand it was shed from (shed_from), and why.
- Categories: context_pressure, traversal_bias, authorial_choice,   practical_constraint.
- Open questions carry forward unless resolved. Curate them.
- instructions_for_next is branch prediction for the next cycle.

Distinguish empirical findings from speculation. Keep specific numbers.


## Prior Tensor (cycle 1)

{
  "cycle": 1,
  "strands": [
    {
      "title": "Monolith Extraction Strategy",
      "content": "A 500K LOC Java/Tomcat monolith requires scoped extraction focused on highest-ROI services. The core insight is that full decomposition is infeasible in typical timelines (6 months). Instead, prioritize extraction by value and constraint. Payments is the strategic entry point because PCI-DSS compliance creates a forcing function: isolating payments dramatically reduces audit scope, liability surface, and engineering friction for all remaining work. The extraction order is (1) Payments (Month 1-2), (2) Auth/Identity (Month 2-3), (3) Inventory (Month 3-5), (4) Stabilization (Month 6). Order Fulfillment is deliberately left in the monolith because it acts as connective tissue touching all other domains; extracting it before its dependencies are services creates more coupling, not less. This is a pragmatic constraint-based ordering, not a theoretical one.",
      "depends_on": [],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "PCI-DSS scope reduction justifies entire payment service extraction to leadership and auditors",
          "truth": 0.92,
          "indeterminacy": 0.07,
          "falsity": 0.01
        },
        {
          "text": "Full monolith decomposition is infeasible in 6-month windows with limited budget",
          "truth": 0.88,
          "indeterminacy": 0.1,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "Order Fulfillment should remain in monolith during first extraction phase due to coupling to all other domains",
          "truth": 0.85,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.03
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Payment Extraction Technical Approach",
      "content": "Payment extraction follows the Strangler Fig pattern with three phases. Phase 1 (Week 1-2) identifies the seam: all call sites into payment logic via grep (typically 15-40 sites), categorized as direct operations, status queries, or incidental coupling. Phase 2 (Week 2-6) strangles by introducing a PaymentGateway interface in the monolith, initially backed by local code, then gradually switched to RemotePaymentGateway calling the service over HTTP. Feature flags enable dual-path production testing. Phase 3 (Week 4-8) untangles data: the payment service gets its own database; the monolith stores only payment_transaction_id references and queries the service API for details. This breaks some SQL reporting but is mandatory for true service isolation. The approach avoids rewriting; it lifts existing logic intact and refactors after production stability is proven.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Monolith Extraction Strategy"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Strangler Fig pattern with feature flags enables dual-path production comparison before full cutover",
          "truth": 0.89,
          "indeterminacy": 0.09,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "Shared databases between services is functionally a distributed monolith with added latency",
          "truth": 0.91,
          "indeterminacy": 0.07,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "Typical monolith payment integrations have 15-40 distinct call sites",
          "truth": 0.75,
          "indeterminacy": 0.2,
          "falsity": 0.05
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Infrastructure and Communication Decisions",
      "content": "Payment service deployment uses synchronous REST/gRPC APIs, not event-driven architecture or message queues. Teams that introduce Kafka for first extractions waste 3+ months on infrastructure with minimal delivered value. Concrete requirements: service communication via REST with OpenAPI versioning; mTLS between monolith and payment service (PCI requirement); isolated PostgreSQL database with encryption at rest and separate credentials; network isolation (PCI requirement). Local dev experience requires Docker Compose from day one so engineers can run monolith + payment-service + payment-db together. Contract testing (Pact or Spring Cloud Contract) is mandatory to catch interface breakage; integration tests are slow and should be minimized. Distributed transaction handling uses Saga pattern with eventual consistency: orders created in PENDING state, payment service called, orders updated to CONFIRMED/FAILED. Latency impact (2ms local to 15-50ms network) requires auditing hot paths; payment status checks in loops must be batched before extraction.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Payment Extraction Technical Approach"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Synchronous REST/gRPC is correct for first extraction; async patterns added when actually needed",
          "truth": 0.87,
          "indeterminacy": 0.11,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "Payment service latency increases from ~2ms in-process to 15-50ms over network",
          "truth": 0.8,
          "indeterminacy": 0.15,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "mTLS and network isolation are PCI-DSS requirements for extracted payment services",
          "truth": 0.93,
          "indeterminacy": 0.06,
          "falsity": 0.01
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Antipatterns and Failure Modes",
      "content": "Four common failure modes undermine monolith extraction projects. (1) Extraction sequencing: teams extract 'easy' services first thinking they'll learn and build confidence. This teaches wrong lessons\u2014easy extractions hide the real constraints. Payments is harder but has clearer boundaries and higher ROI; extracting it first catches distributed transaction complexity early. (2) Infrastructure goldplating: teams build service meshes, API gateways, or full Kubernetes setups before any service exists. The payment service ships on a VM behind a load balancer; infrastructure evolves after operational experience. (3) Scope creep via redesign: teams attempt to redesign payment logic during extraction. This combines two high-risk projects into one. Lift-and-shift existing logic, prove stability, then refactor with coverage. (4) Shared databases: maintaining shared schemas between monolith and payment service creates a distributed monolith with network latency and transactional complexity. Each service owns its data; the monolith references it by ID only.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Payment Extraction Technical Approach",
        "Infrastructure and Communication Decisions"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Extracting 'easy' services first teaches teams wrong lessons about distributed complexity",
          "truth": 0.83,
          "indeterminacy": 0.14,
          "falsity": 0.03
        },
        {
          "text": "Service mesh/API gateway/Kubernetes goldplating delays value delivery and should be deferred",
          "truth": 0.86,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "Simultaneous migration and redesign combines two high-risk projects and typically causes failure",
          "truth": 0.88,
          "indeterminacy": 0.1,
          "falsity": 0.02
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Auth Service as Second Extraction",
      "content": "Auth/Identity extraction follows payments (Month 2-3) because every future service requires it. This becomes the pattern-setter for identity across the platform. Auth should be extracted as a proper OpenID Connect / OAuth2 provider so downstream services consume a standard protocol, not custom auth logic. The payment service becomes the first consumer of this auth service, validating the interface. Deferring auth extraction leads to auth logic duplication in each subsequent service (inventory, etc.), compounding technical debt. Extraction timing is constrained: must come before inventory extraction, should come early enough to establish identity patterns while teams still have extraction momentum.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Monolith Extraction Strategy"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Auth service should be second extraction to prevent auth logic duplication in future services",
          "truth": 0.86,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "OpenID Connect / OAuth2 is appropriate standard protocol for auth service in 500K LOC monolith context",
          "truth": 0.89,
          "indeterminacy": 0.09,
          "falsity": 0.02
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "open_questions": [
    "What is the current payment integration model: direct processor calls (Stripe, Adyen) or internal abstraction layer? This significantly affects extraction complexity.",
    "Does the 500K LOC monolith have existing test coverage, especially around payment logic? Extraction difficulty scales with test gaps.",
    "What is the actual 6-month timeline constraint? Is this a hard deadline driven by compliance, budget, or organizational priority?",
    "Are there cross-functional dependencies (order fulfillment touching payments, inventory, notifications) that are more complex than assumed?",
    "Does the organization have experience with distributed systems and eventual consistency, or is this the first service extraction?",
    "What is the current CI/CD maturity? Can the monolith and new payment service be deployed independently with confidence?"
  ],
  "instructions_for_next": "\nNext cycle should focus on: (1) user clarifies current payment integration architecture (processor vs. internal abstraction), (2) mapping actual call sites and data dependencies from their codebase, (3) compliance team alignment on PCI scope reduction. If user provides payment integration details, shift to detailed Phase 1 (seam identification) planning. If user raises timeline concerns, be prepared to de-risk with smaller scope (e.g., extract only payment query API in month 1, charge/refund in month 2). If organization has no service extraction experience, add spike work for Strangler Fig proof-of-concept before full payment extraction. Keep focus on extracting payments and auth; resist scope expansion to order fulfillment or additional services.\n",
  "declared_losses": []
}

