      "content": "The 6-month migration achieves resilience, deployment isolation, and PCI compliance through a modular monolith architecture with strategic extraction of the Payments service only. The core principle: \"Separate what must be separate legally or operationally; leave tight-coupled domains together until data proves otherwise.\" Modular monolith structure uses strict build-time enforcement (ArchUnit, NetArchTest, dependency-cruiser) to prevent illegal cross-module dependencies, separate database schemas within the same instance, and internal event bus for decoupled communication. Each module (Inventory, Orders, Auth, Payments) exposes a public interface; no internal implementation is visible across boundaries. Payments extraction is justified on three dimensions: (1) PCI-DSS compliance scope reduction\u2014extraction shrinks the cardholder data environment (CDE) massively, reducing audit burden and costs; (2) Cleanest interface boundary\u2014payment service takes requests, returns results, no complex joins across inventory/order data; (3) Operational isolation\u2014payment service can fail independently, orders queue gracefully without system-wide impact. Extracting other services (inventory, orders, auth) in the 6-month window introduces distributed transaction overhead, saga pattern complexity, and eventual consistency bugs that don't exist in a single-database monolith. Auth extraction is particularly expensive: every request would require a network hop to validate tokens, overhead for zero resilience gain (library-based auth is sufficient). Inventory-Orders extraction couples to data model changes (separate schema joins, no transactions across services), distributed query patterns, and Saga orchestration that consumes the remaining 6 months. This architecture ships, passes audit, and defers further extraction decisions until team size (8+ engineers), scaling pressure (10x independent demand), or infrastructure needs (real-time ML, streaming) justify it.",
